Introduction {#S1}
============

The spontaneous activity of the brain at rest is spatially and temporally organized in large-scale networks of cortical and subcortical regions, denoted Resting State Networks (RSNs). The topography of RSNs is similar to that of brain networks recruited by different cognitive tasks ([@B5]; [@B1]; [@B22]), and for this reason RSNs have been named according to their putative function and pattern of task activation: dorsal and ventral attention, visual, somato-motor, auditory, language, executive control, and default systems ([@B20]; [@B25]; [@B23]). As behavior unfolds, these functionally specific systems must integrate to ensure efficient processing and transfer of information in the brain. The dynamic interplay among RSNs supports cognitive flexibility and the brain's ability to adapt to varying demands. Recent advances in neuroimaging techniques, such as functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) and magnetoencephalography (MEG), have enabled the exploration of temporal fluctuations within and between these networks, revealing patterns of functional connectivity that are both stable and transient over time ([@B12]; [@B18]). Understanding the mechanisms underlying RSN integration and segregation is critical for elucidating the neural basis of cognition and its disruption in neurological and psychiatric disorders.

