Introduction {#s1}
============

Lysergic acid diethylamide (LSD) is a prototypical hallucinogen ([@CIT0019]; [@CIT0020]). LSD became famous as a psychedelic in the 1960s, and its recreational use continues ([@CIT0020]). Pharmacologically, LSD acts primarily as a partial agonist at serotonin 5-HT2A receptors, which is believed to underlie its profound effects on perception, cognition, and mood ([@CIT0021]). The compound's unique ability to induce altered states of consciousness has made it a valuable tool in both neuroscience research and psychotherapy ([@CIT0022]; [@CIT0023]). Despite its classification as a Schedule I substance in many countries, recent studies have revisited LSD's potential therapeutic applications, particularly in the treatment of anxiety, depression, and substance use disorders ([@CIT0024]; [@CIT0025]). This review aims to provide a comprehensive overview of LSD's pharmacology, psychological effects, and emerging clinical uses.

